    A dynamically-sized collection, wrapping ArrayList.

      • get

        public T get(int index)
        Returns the nth element in the list. If n is negative, then the index is the offset from the end, where -1 is the last element, -2 is the second to last element, and so on and so forth. If n is out of range (not within 0 ... size()), then null is returned.
        Specified by:
        get in interface java.util.List<T>
        Overrides:
        get in class java.util.ArrayList<T>

      • get

        public List<T> get(int fromIndex,
                   int toIndex)
        Returns a List containing the mth element through the nth element in the list, both inclusive. If m n is negative, then the index is the offset from the end, where -1 is the last element, -2 is the second to last element, and so on and so forth. If m or n is out of range (not within 0 ... size()), then an empty set is returned.

      • append

        public List<T> append(T obj)
        Adds the element to the list, and returns the list, so this method can be chained: 
            List<Integer> nums = List.of(1, 2, 3);
    nums.append(4).append(5);
        See Also:
        List.add(E)

      • set

        public T set(int index,
             T value)
        Sets the nth element in the list. If n is negative, then the index is the offset from the end, where -1 is the last element, -2 is the second to last element. Unlike ArrayList#set, this method honors the dynamically sized aspect of the list, and resizes it accordingly when set(index, obj) && index > size(). However, set(-index, obj) (a negative index value) will result in an IllegalArgumentException when -index > -size().
        Specified by:
        set in interface java.util.List<T>
        Overrides:
        set in class java.util.ArrayList<T>

      • elements
